Furthermore, sensitivity analysis is a crucial tool to assess the stability and reliability of the results. It ranks the MSSs (alternatives) with the change of criteria (sub-MSRs) weights. In this study, a total of 37 cases are tested. The weights of sub-MSRs kept “tremendously high” (TH) one by one while keeping the weights of other sub-MSRs low or equal. For instance, in case 1, the weight of ENR1 is allocated TH, and the remaining sub-MSRs (ENR2-GPR6) weights are assumed to be equal. Details of all cases are presented in Table D1 (
                        Appendix D
                     ). MSS4 consistently ranked first in all 37 cases, and MSS25 achieved the second rank in 36 cases (Figs. 4 and 5

                     ). Spearman's rank correlation coefficient was calculated, showing a strong association (average value of 0.9821) between the final ranking and sensitivity analysis cases.
